We work in the ring of all $2 \times 2$ upper triangular matrices over $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$, with matrix addition and multiplication performed entrywise modulo $2$. Let's choose two matrices from this set, for example:
$$
A=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 1 \\ 0 & 1\end{pmatrix}, \qquad B=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
$$
Both matrices are in $S$ since their entries are in $\{0,1\}$ and they are upper triangular.

Using standard matrix multiplication, with all arithmetic performed modulo $2$, we compute the product $AB$:
$$
AB=\begin{pmatrix}
1\cdot 1+1\cdot 0 & 1\cdot 0+1\cdot 0 \\
0\cdot 1+1\cdot 0 & 0\cdot 0+1\cdot 0
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
$$
Next, we compute the product $BA$:
$$
BA=\begin{pmatrix}
1\cdot 1+0\cdot 0 & 1\cdot 1+0\cdot 1 \\
0\cdot 1+0\cdot 0 & 0\cdot 1+0\cdot 1
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 1 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
$$
Since $AB \neq BA$, we have demonstrated that the ring is non-commutative. The problem asks for the difference $AB - BA$. In $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$, subtraction is the same as addition, since $-1 \equiv 1 \pmod 2$.
$$
AB - BA = \begin{pmatrix}1-1 & 0-1 \\ 0-0 & 0-0\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}0 & -1 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}
$$
Thus the requested matrix is $\begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}$.
